    30→### Parsing ambiguity …
    79→#### Alternative: Make `--` part of your syntax
    81→Rather than trying to teach your users what `--` does, you could just make it part of your syntax.
    82→
    83→```js
    84→program.usage('[options] -- [technique]');
    85→```
    86→
      →…
   104→#### Alternative: Put options last
   106→Commander follows the GNU convention for parsing and allows options before or after the command-arguments, or intermingled.
   107→So by putting the options last, the command-arguments do not get confused with the option-arguments.
   108→
   109→```js
   110→program.usage('[technique] [options]');
   111→```
      →…
   126→#### Alternative: Use options instead of command-arguments
   128→This is a bit more radical, but completely avoids the parsing ambiguity!
   129→
   130→```js
   131→program
   132→  .name('cook')
   133→  .option('-t, --technique <technique>', 'cooking technique')
      →…
   148→## Combining short options, and options taking arguments
   150→Multiple boolean short options can be combined after a single `-`, like `ls -al`. You can also include just
   151→a single short option which might take a value, as any following characters will
   152→be taken as the value.
   153→
